<L>Plea&s;ed on the boiling wave old AESON &s;wims,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P><HI>Plea&s;ed on the boiling wave.</HI> l. 387. The &s;tory of Ae&s;on becoming young, from the medicated bath of Medea, &s;eems to have been intended to teach the efficacy of warm bathing in retarding the progre&s;s of old age. The words <HI>relaxation and bracing,</HI> which are generally thought expre&s;&s;ive of the effects of warm and cold bathing, are mechanical terms, properly applied to drums or &s;trings; but are only metaphors when applied to the effects of cold or warm bathing on animal bodies. The immediate cau&s;e of old age &s;eems to re&s;ide in the inirritability of the finer ve&s;&s;els or parts of our &s;y&s;tem; hence the&s;e cea&s;e to act, and collap&s;e or become horny or bony. The warm bath is peculiarly adapted to prevent the&s;e circum&s;tances by its increa&s;ing our irritability, and by moi&s;ten|ing and &s;oftening the &s;kin, and the extremities of the finer ve&s;&s;els, which terminate in it. To tho&s;e who are pa&s;t the meridian of life, and have dry &s;kins, and begin to be emaciated, the warm bath, for half an hour twice a week, I believe to be eminently ferviceable in retarding the advances of age.</P></NOTE></L>
