<L>The fair HELLEBORAS attractive &s;hone,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P><HI>Helleborus.</HI> l. 201. Many males, many females. The Helleborus niger, or Chri&s;t|mas ro&s;e, has a large beautiful white flower, adorned with a circle of tubular two-lipp'd nectaries. After impregnation the flower undergoes a remarkable change, the nectaries, drop off, but the white corol remains, and gradually becomes quite green. This curious metamorph &s;e of the corol, when the nectaries fall off, &s;eems to &s;hew that the white juices of the corol were before carried to the nectaries, for the purpo&s;e of producing honey: becau&s;e when the&s;e nectaries fall off, no more of the white juice is &s;ecreted in the corol, but it becomes green, and degenerates into a calyx. See note on Lonicera. The nectary of the Tropaeolum, garden na&s;turtien, is a coloured horn grewing from the calyx.</P></NOTE></L>
